Continue in the things that you learned and were persuaded to believe. - 2 Timothy 3:14

## intro
- Will you 'continue to speak'?
- 2 ti 3:14 - things learned....persuaded...learned study note.
- Basic principle: To be a servant of Jehovah is to be taught, to be a lifelong learner. And because we imitate our grand instructor, it means that we also become lifelong teachers.
- special need in the organization for trained workers. including work skills but especially spiritual skills.

## main points
- 1 Sam 9:15,16 - Saul to be annointed
	- Samuel not for the idea, could have just annointed him nad left.
- 1 Sam 9:22 - invited him for a meal
	- Made an arrangment
	- no doubt spoke to him during the occasion
- 1 Sam 9:25 - Continued to speak to Saul 
- ![2022-11-08 saul and samuel.jpg](data:image/png;base64,)
	- continued to give training that he would need in his new assignment
	- do we continue to speak, by giving training at every opportunity?

## conclusion
- Learn that we train even if we are training our replacement
- We plan ahead to train/learn others
- We continue to speak - we use every opportunity to train/learn
- blessing:
	- The author learns more than the reader.
	- The speaker learns more than the attendee.
	- The teacher learns more than the student.
	- The way to learn is by doing.

## question
- In order to train others, we need to have a strong faith ourselves

## references
*** w15 4/15 pp. 4-5 par. 7 Elders, How Do You Feel About Training Others? ***
Clearly, then, we should guard against thinking that training is of low priority. Elders who take a long-range view and invest their time in training less experienced brothers are wise stewards and a true blessing to the entire congregation. (Read 1 Peter 4:10.) How does the congregation benefit?

*** w15 4/15 p. 5 par. 8 Elders, How Do You Feel About Training Others? ***
Even the most experienced elders must modestly recognize that advancing age will gradually limit the amount of work they personally can do for the congregation. (Mic. 6:8) Also, they should realistically take into account that “time and unexpected events” may bring about a sudden change in their ability to care for congregation responsibilities. (Eccl. 9:11, 12; Jas. 4:13, 14) So out of heartfelt concern for the well-being of Jehovah’s sheep, forward-looking elders share in a timely fashion with younger brothers the experience they have acquired during their years of faithful service.
